But the 990 elites who don't get a chair don't just go home quietly, do they?

29:19.180 --> 29:19.820
No, they don't.

29:19.880 --> 29:25.160
They start actively trying to burn down the building, or they launch revolutions just to

29:25.160 --> 29:26.560
create new chairs for themselves.

29:26.560 --> 29:31.960
History is replete with revolutions led not by the starving peasants, but by the frustrated

29:31.960 --> 29:33.640
second-tier elites.

29:34.480 --> 29:37.940
But once again, Flyxion's paper doesn't just settle for the historical narrative.

29:38.400 --> 29:41.700
It translates this political dynamic into hard geometry.

29:41.860 --> 29:42.320
Yes.

29:42.520 --> 29:47.820
And here is where we get the most crucial, eye-opening deep dive of the entire document.

29:47.980 --> 29:52.660
Example 1, the worked mathematical example of the CLIO projection.

29:52.980 --> 29:54.360
Here's where it gets really interesting.

29:54.360 --> 29:58.560
I want to walk through this math step-by-step with you, because when I understood this,

29:58.640 --> 30:03.180
it felt like discovering the Rosetta Stone for why complex organizations fail.

