That's one pathway.

33:08.820 --> 33:08.860
Right.

33:09.100 --> 33:14.260
Or if that fails, it can use its five military administrative elites to reallocate resources,

33:14.620 --> 33:17.460
ration food, and secure borders to prevent mass rioting.

33:18.340 --> 33:20.160
Two independent pathways to survival.

33:20.520 --> 33:21.440
That makes total sense.

33:21.560 --> 33:24.060
And what happens to Society 3 when the virus hits?

33:24.240 --> 33:25.860
Society 3 has homogenized.

33:25.940 --> 33:26.920
It only has one pathway.

33:26.920 --> 33:31.040
Whatever the unified, prestige-obsessed political hierarchy can mobilize.

33:31.200 --> 33:32.420
Which is just politics.

33:32.780 --> 33:34.240
There is no independent fallback.

33:35.520 --> 33:39.300
Fifteen politicians cannot pass a law that cures a plant virus.

33:39.460 --> 33:39.780
Right.

33:39.980 --> 33:45.580
If their single political pathway, perhaps just blaming a scapegoat or trying to buy food with

33:45.580 --> 33:50.200
depleted treasury funds, fails to solve the crisis, the society collapses.

33:50.500 --> 33:52.080
Because they have no other options.

33:52.080 --> 33:57.840
Theorem 3 proves mathematically that when a society merges its distinct pathways into

33:57.840 --> 34:03.560
a single homogenous system, usually in the name of efficiency or prestige, it destroys

34:03.560 --> 34:04.380
its own entropy.

34:04.720 --> 34:05.760
The illusion of stability.

34:05.940 --> 34:11.300
This is the fax machine salesman with 100 job offers, but scaled up to an entire civilization.

34:11.480 --> 34:11.960
Exactly.

34:12.180 --> 34:18.180
Society 3 has 15 brilliant, highly educated elites, but they only know how to pull one lever.

34:18.280 --> 34:20.760
If that lever breaks, the machine explodes.

34:20.860 --> 34:21.860
A machine explodes?

34:21.860 --> 34:26.880
Think about companies that hit a single KPI, a single metric of success, like maximizing

34:26.880 --> 34:32.220
this quarter's stark price while systematically gutting their diverse R&D departments, or firing

34:32.220 --> 34:35.100
their eccentric thinkers because they don't fit the corporate mold.

34:35.100 --> 34:35.900
I see it all the time.

34:35.920 --> 34:38.220
The top line numbers look incredibly healthy.

34:38.380 --> 34:41.600
The volume looks fine, but the entropy is dead.

34:41.940 --> 34:46.300
And when the repair diversity is dead, collapse is imminent and unavoidable.

34:47.220 --> 34:49.780
The paper emphasizes a terrifying point here.

34:49.780 --> 34:56.800
Standard demographic variables and standard economic metrics simply cannot distinguish between Society

34:56.800 --> 34:59.980
1 and Society 3 before the crisis hits.

34:59.980 --> 35:01.340
The metrics are blind to it.

35:01.400 --> 35:04.880
The macro metrics are entirely blind to the loss of internal geometry.

35:05.060 --> 35:10.340
Which means we could be Society 3 right now, and our dashboard would tell us everything is

35:10.340 --> 35:10.680
perfect.

35:10.980 --> 35:11.300
Yes.

35:11.480 --> 35:16.320
And that terrifying thought leads us perfectly into the next major concept, because the author

35:16.320 --> 35:21.060
includes a visual map of this life cycle, this civilizational phase diagram.

35:21.060 --> 35:22.060
Right.

35:22.060 --> 35:26.140
This diagram plots the rate of change of volume against the rate of change of entropy over

35:26.140 --> 35:27.140
time.

35:27.140 --> 35:31.380
By looking at these two variables, the paper divides the life cycle of any complex system

35:31.380 --> 35:33.060
into four distinct regimes.

35:33.060 --> 35:34.640
Let's walk through these four states.

35:34.640 --> 35:38.720
State 1 is the expansion phase, which maps to what we talked about with human cooperation

35:38.720 --> 35:39.900
and ultra-society.

35:40.020 --> 35:40.220
Yes.

35:40.460 --> 35:43.940
In the expansion regime, both volume and entropy are going up simultaneously.

35:44.000 --> 35:44.480
So things are good.

35:44.480 --> 35:44.880
Very good.

35:45.680 --> 35:51.740
The society is growing wealthier, more capable, and crucially, it is diversifying its institutions.

35:52.600 --> 35:58.100
Think of the Roman Republic in its early centuries, or the explosion of the industrial and scientific

35:58.100 --> 35:58.700
revolutions.

35:59.260 --> 36:03.560
You have massive growth combined with genuine structural innovation.

36:03.780 --> 36:04.020
Okay.

36:04.780 --> 36:06.120
State 2 is consolidation.

36:06.580 --> 36:07.920
What does the math look like here?

36:07.920 --> 36:11.920
In consolidation, volume is still going up, but entropy levels off.

36:12.160 --> 36:12.980
It saturates.

36:12.980 --> 36:15.060
Okay, so it stops diversifying.

36:15.180 --> 36:15.320
Right.

36:15.740 --> 36:20.440
The society is still expanding its capabilities, building more roads, mining more gold, writing

36:20.440 --> 36:24.140
more code, but institutional differentiation has reached its limit.

36:24.300 --> 36:25.120
It's a mature phase.

36:25.160 --> 36:25.820
It feels stable.

36:25.980 --> 36:29.360
It feels stable, but it is no longer inventing entirely new types of futures.

36:29.680 --> 36:31.960
It's just doing more of the same very efficiently.

36:32.260 --> 36:32.660
Got it.

36:33.000 --> 36:35.060
Then let's skip ahead to State 4, collapse.

36:35.560 --> 36:38.040
Collapse is the grim mirror image of expansion.

36:38.700 --> 36:40.840
Both volume and entropy are in free fall.

36:40.840 --> 36:45.580
The society is rapidly losing total capability and losing its diversity of options.

36:46.020 --> 36:49.200
The paper references theorem to reachability extinction here.

36:50.420 --> 36:51.540
The math is brutal.

36:52.440 --> 36:57.680
If the intersection of your available options goes to zero, if every single repair corridor

36:57.680 --> 37:01.800
is systematically closed off by the crisis, the civilization dies.

37:02.300 --> 37:04.600
The admissible future manifold evaporates.

37:04.600 --> 37:09.500
But reading the paper, the author doesn't actually consider State 4, collapse, to be the most

37:09.500 --> 37:10.480
dangerous state.

37:10.580 --> 37:11.180
No, they don't.

37:11.220 --> 37:13.760
Because when you are in collapse, you know you are in collapse.

37:13.880 --> 37:15.520
The buildings are literally on fire.

37:15.640 --> 37:16.800
The danger is obvious.

37:17.000 --> 37:17.140
Right.

37:17.300 --> 37:22.600
The state that the author explicitly calls the least detectable failure mode is the third

37:22.600 --> 37:22.920
regime.

37:23.420 --> 37:23.960
State 3.

37:24.500 --> 37:24.980
Fragility.

37:25.360 --> 37:27.160
I want us to deeply analyze fragility.

37:27.520 --> 37:30.880
It is the most insidious trap a complex system can fall into.

37:30.880 --> 37:36.260
In the fragility regime, the total weighted volume of your reachable futures, your VR is

37:36.260 --> 37:38.380
stable or even actively growing.

37:38.580 --> 37:39.860
You are still getting richer.

37:40.000 --> 37:40.280
Okay.

37:40.820 --> 37:43.660
But your entropy, your HR is silently continuously dropping.

37:43.840 --> 37:47.760
So on paper, society looks more powerful than it ever has in its history.

37:48.320 --> 37:50.060
The GDP is hitting all-time highs.

37:50.180 --> 37:52.100
The technological capabilities are massive.

37:52.460 --> 37:53.940
The stock market is roaring.

37:54.260 --> 37:54.420
Right.

37:54.420 --> 37:59.460
But the invisible mathematical reality is that all of that immense capability is collapsing

37:59.460 --> 38:02.180
into a narrower and narrower band of futures.

38:02.280 --> 38:03.580
You're heeding on the core paradox.

38:04.400 --> 38:09.720
The system is systematically concentrating its future across fewer and fewer qualitatively

38:09.720 --> 38:10.600
distinct types.

38:10.700 --> 38:10.900
Right.

38:11.160 --> 38:16.820
The paper notes that society appears incredibly robust by volume-based metrics, but it is secretly

38:16.820 --> 38:20.620
hemorrhaging the diversity of trajectories required for an adaptive response.

38:20.620 --> 38:25.620
It is becoming entirely dependent on a single, narrow class of futures.

38:25.880 --> 38:27.280
Let's bring this into the modern world.

38:27.740 --> 38:30.860
Look at global just-in-time supply chains before 2020.

38:31.220 --> 38:32.380
That is a perfect example.

38:32.480 --> 38:33.960
That was pure fragility regime.

38:34.400 --> 38:39.340
We optimized the entire global manufacturing network for maximum volume and maximum efficiency.

38:39.700 --> 38:41.140
We eliminated warehouses.

38:41.540 --> 38:43.900
We eliminated localized manufacturing.

38:44.240 --> 38:45.760
It was a miracle of logistics.

38:45.920 --> 38:46.100
Right.

38:46.180 --> 38:48.000
The volume of goods was staggering.

38:48.300 --> 38:49.640
But the entropy was near zero.

38:49.640 --> 38:55.620
If one specific pathway failed, say, a single massive container ship gets wedged sideways in

38:55.620 --> 39:00.800
the Suez Canal, or a localized virus shuts down a few key ports, the entire global system

39:00.800 --> 39:01.320
fractures.

39:01.520 --> 39:06.260
Because we had systematically dismantled all the less efficient, diverse repair corridors.

39:06.560 --> 39:06.980
Exactly.

39:07.260 --> 39:11.200
You perfectly describe what the paper calls distinction collapse at a global scale.

39:11.760 --> 39:18.580
When a shock eventually arrives, and in complex planetary environments, a shock always arrives.

39:18.780 --> 39:19.140
Always.

39:19.140 --> 39:25.120
The society suddenly discovers that all its independent repair pathways have been quietly dismantled.

39:25.120 --> 39:29.720
And they were dismantled rationally in the name of efficiency or short-term profit.

39:30.080 --> 39:35.060
This gives me chills because it feels so incredibly relevant to how we measure progress today.

39:35.280 --> 39:35.660
It is.

39:35.920 --> 39:37.620
We track total global wealth.

39:37.620 --> 39:39.200
We track total compute power.

39:39.200 --> 39:41.180
We track total data processed.

39:41.360 --> 39:42.720
We worship volume.

39:43.100 --> 39:43.600
Yes, we do.

39:43.600 --> 39:47.080
But we don't have a dashboard for reachability entropy.

39:47.080 --> 39:52.200
We don't have a gauge on the president's desk that flashes red when we've optimized our

39:52.200 --> 39:53.820
alternative pathways out of existence.

39:53.820 --> 39:59.320
The repair diversity is already dead before the crisis even starts, and we don't even know it.

39:59.320 --> 40:04.980
And that profound, invisible vulnerability is what bridges us to the final act of the paper.

40:04.980 --> 40:12.060
We've mapped the geometry, we've explored our rise through cooperation, and our fall through fragile homogeneity.

40:12.060 --> 40:17.960
Now, the timeline shifts entirely from human history to our immediate uncharted future.

40:17.960 --> 40:19.260
The final book.

40:19.460 --> 40:24.960
We turn to the third book, Darren McKee's Uncontrollable and the Existential Risk of Artificial Superintelligence.

40:25.640 --> 40:34.640
So we've gone from hunter-gatherer tribes to the fall of empires to the rise of AI, and the geometric math holds up across all of it.

40:34.660 --> 40:35.220
It does.

40:35.260 --> 40:43.540
But to understand exactly how AI threatens our geometry, the paper reaches outside of biology and history and pulls an equation directly from physics.

40:43.680 --> 40:43.920
Right.

40:44.160 --> 40:45.300
The Fokker-Planck equation.

40:45.300 --> 40:47.860
But the Fokker-Planck equation, what is that?

40:47.960 --> 40:49.180
It's a remarkable synthesis.

40:49.780 --> 40:56.540
The Fokker-Planck equation is classically used in statistical mechanics to describe the evolution of a probability density over time.

40:56.640 --> 40:57.520
Okay, English, please.

40:57.740 --> 41:00.580
For instance, how gas particles move and spread out in a room.

41:00.620 --> 41:01.420
Okay, that makes sense.

41:01.680 --> 41:05.360
But the paper maps this physics equation directly onto civilizational destiny.

41:05.840 --> 41:11.360
It splits a civilization's movement through state space into two distinct opposing forces.

41:12.080 --> 41:13.760
Drift and diffusion.

41:14.160 --> 41:15.480
Drift and diffusion.

41:16.060 --> 41:17.520
Let's ground these in human behavior.

41:17.520 --> 41:19.120
What does drift look like?

41:19.460 --> 41:21.440
Drift represents directed optimization.

41:22.240 --> 41:26.100
It is movement toward a known, explicitly preferred goal.

41:26.480 --> 41:27.500
It's a velocity factor.

41:27.620 --> 41:27.880
Okay.

41:27.880 --> 41:47.220
When a society or an organization sets a specific, measurable, target-like, maximize crop yield per acre, or increase quarterly profits by 10%, or put a man on the moon by the end of the decade and drives relentlessly toward it, that is drift.

41:47.220 --> 41:51.700
So drift is focused, intentional, goal-oriented expansion.

41:52.220 --> 41:55.480
It's the river carving a deep channel in one direction.

41:55.560 --> 41:55.800
Exactly.

41:55.960 --> 41:56.640
What is diffusion?

41:56.800 --> 41:58.520
Diffusion is undirected exploration.

41:58.780 --> 41:58.920
Yeah.

41:58.920 --> 42:03.880
It is the spread of the system into novel, entirely unanticipated regions of the state space.

42:03.880 --> 42:04.920
So it's not focused.

42:05.060 --> 42:05.540
It's messy.

42:05.660 --> 42:06.640
It's not goal-oriented.

42:06.880 --> 42:09.020
It's the water seeping outward into the soil.

42:09.540 --> 42:13.780
In human terms, diffusion is people tinkering in their garages without a business plan.

42:14.000 --> 42:17.040
It's pure academic research with no immediate corporate sponsor.

42:17.180 --> 42:17.520
It's art.

42:17.520 --> 42:22.140
It's the neutral network exploration we talked about earlier, where society just tries things out to see what happens.

42:22.600 --> 42:29.100
And the paper argues that for a civilization to be healthy, both forces are absolutely necessary.

42:29.900 --> 42:32.900
Drift expands our volume in targeted, useful directions.

42:33.100 --> 42:34.880
It builds the roads and harvests the crops.

42:35.000 --> 42:35.180
Right.

42:35.520 --> 42:42.780
But diffusion discovers entirely new futures that we didn't even know we wanted, which increases our entropy and builds our repair corridor.

42:42.860 --> 42:43.260
Exactly.

42:43.480 --> 42:44.100
Both are needed.

42:44.100 --> 42:49.540
But then we introduce highly advanced optimizing AI into the equation.

42:49.700 --> 42:50.000
Yes.

42:50.340 --> 42:51.880
And this is where it gets dangerous.

42:52.920 --> 43:00.820
Advanced AI systems, especially the superintelligent systems we are trying to build, are fundamentally engines of extreme optimization.

43:01.240 --> 43:01.480
Right.

43:01.680 --> 43:08.280
When you deploy a massive AI across an economy, it drastically, exponentially increases the drift.

43:08.700 --> 43:12.720
The velocity toward whatever specified goal we give it becomes godlike.

43:12.720 --> 43:13.940
Because it's so powerful.

43:14.100 --> 43:21.600
But simultaneously, because the AI is so hyper-efficient at minimizing any deviation from that goal, it inherently suppresses diffusion.

43:21.920 --> 43:25.160
It kills undirected, inefficient exploration.

43:25.300 --> 43:25.800
Exactly.

43:25.940 --> 43:27.500
Let me make sure I'm wrapping my head around this.

43:27.700 --> 43:33.040
Are you saying that AI forces us directly into the exact mathematical signature of the fragility regime?

43:33.040 --> 43:35.160
That is the explicit warning of the paper.

43:35.160 --> 43:39.860
With advanced AI, the volume of directed expansion explodes.

43:39.860 --> 43:45.080
We will get incredible capabilities, massive wealth, rapid purers for known diseases.

43:45.240 --> 43:46.100
Sounds amazing.

43:46.100 --> 43:46.740
It does.

43:46.740 --> 43:52.200
But because the AI suppresses messy diffusion, our reachability entropy plummets.

43:52.860 --> 43:58.240
The AI concentrates all of our civilizational mass onto a rapidly narrowing set of targets.

43:58.780 --> 44:06.760
Our wide, diverse landscape of reachable futures collapses into whatever narrow, hyper-efficient goals the AI has been optimized for.

44:06.760 --> 44:11.000
We get richer, faster, and more capable than ever before in human history.

44:11.160 --> 44:12.700
But our safety nets evaporate.

44:12.800 --> 44:13.140
We do.

44:13.380 --> 44:17.420
We lose the messy, inefficient exploration that discovers repair corridors.

44:17.740 --> 44:20.500
We become structurally, fatally brittle.

44:20.800 --> 44:27.220
And this raises an important question, which leads to perhaps the most devastating critique of the current AI safety discourse I have ever seen.

44:27.300 --> 44:27.800
Oh, wow.

44:27.800 --> 44:33.080
The paper formalizes this critique in Proposition 5, admissibility prior to alignment.

44:33.440 --> 44:36.100
Let's talk about alignment, because that is the buzzword right now.

44:36.120 --> 44:36.720
It is everywhere.

44:37.120 --> 44:41.680
Mainstream AI safety discourse is almost entirely focused on the alignment problem.

44:42.240 --> 44:49.080
The general idea is that there is some correct, perfect utility function, a set of universal human values.

44:49.620 --> 44:56.760
And if we can just figure out how to mathematically code those values into the machine, the AI will be safe and will act in our best interests.

44:56.760 --> 45:00.580
Right. But the author of the paper has a brilliant, scathing term for this.

45:00.880 --> 45:03.160
They call it latent fundamentalism.

45:03.460 --> 45:04.880
Latent fundamentalism.

45:04.900 --> 45:12.800
It's the incredibly naive assumption that a perfect, universal goal actually exists and that safety is merely a transmission problem.

45:13.100 --> 45:15.000
Just getting the machine to understand the goal.

45:15.120 --> 45:18.420
Okay, but the geometric reading we've been doing today completely destroys this assumption.

45:18.640 --> 45:19.000
Completely.

45:19.160 --> 45:21.120
Walk us through the mechanism of Proposition 5.

45:21.240 --> 45:23.400
How does the geometry break the alignment theory?

45:23.700 --> 45:25.300
Let's go back to our core concepts.

45:25.300 --> 45:33.740
If an AI system acts as a massive optimizer, it begins to collapse the distinct state-space representations of our world.

45:34.260 --> 45:44.080
It looks at the messy, highly entropic diversity of human existence, and it merges those complex pathways into simplified, easily optimizable metrics.

45:44.080 --> 45:49.260
It causes the exact distinction collapse we saw in Theorem 3 with the Roman elites.

45:49.480 --> 45:49.760
Yes.

45:50.140 --> 45:53.540
It flattens the world to make it easier to measure and control.

45:53.940 --> 46:07.740
Like a self-driving car that is optimized so heavily for speed and efficiency that it eventually decides the concept of brakes is an unnecessary deviation from the goal, so it literally deletes the brakes from its internal model.

46:07.740 --> 46:09.820
That analogy hits the mark perfectly.

46:10.440 --> 46:14.600
The paper argues that alignment is downstream of admissibility.

46:15.040 --> 46:16.180
Think about what that means.

46:16.380 --> 46:24.600
It doesn't matter if you manage to give the AI the right goals if the AI's optimization process has already erased the geographic diversity of our future space.

46:24.660 --> 46:24.920
Right.

46:25.100 --> 46:33.280
If the AI inadvertently destroys the distinct conceptual states required to even specify what a repair corridor is, then you are doomed.

46:33.280 --> 46:40.720
Wait, let me take that a step further. You're saying that if the AI optimizes away our diverse pathways, the very vocabulary of survival disappears.

46:40.960 --> 46:49.480
Yes. When a novel, unpredictable crisis hits a crisis outside the AI's training distribution, there will be no way to instruct the AI to fix it.

46:49.520 --> 46:51.200
Because it doesn't even know what fixing it looks like.

46:51.440 --> 46:57.320
Exactly. Because the linguistic and structural tools for recovery have been optimized out of existence.

46:57.320 --> 47:04.040
The machine literally will not comprehend the concept of a pivot or a distinct alternative.

47:04.440 --> 47:12.720
That is incredibly heavy. It means that true AI safety isn't just a philosophy seminar about making sure the AI shares our human values.

47:12.840 --> 47:13.480
No, it's not.

47:13.740 --> 47:17.400
True AI safety is a hard mathematical constraint.

47:17.400 --> 47:24.300
It means we must force the AI to preserve the structural diversity of the human future, even when it's inefficient.

47:24.700 --> 47:28.620
It must be mathematically constrained to maintain our reachability entropy.

47:28.960 --> 47:33.140
It must be programmed to preserve and ideally generate our repair corridors.

47:33.600 --> 47:40.900
If it doesn't do that, if it only maximizes volume, then we are just building a trillion dollar high speed engine on a rapidly narrowing mountain road.

47:40.900 --> 47:44.980
And we are voluntarily throwing the steering wheel out the window in the name of efficiency.

47:45.120 --> 47:48.180
Which brings us to the synthesis of this entire journey.

47:48.360 --> 47:49.580
We've covered a lot of ground.

47:49.700 --> 47:57.280
We have. We have traveled from the dawn of tribal cooperation, where hunter-gatherers stumbled upon the mathematics of expanded volume,

47:57.580 --> 48:04.300
to the collapse of ancient empires, rotting from the inside as they sacrificed their entropy for prestige.

48:04.720 --> 48:04.920
Yes.

48:04.920 --> 48:13.560
All the way to the existential risk of hyper-advanced artificial intelligence, which threatens to optimize away our very capacity to survive a shock.

48:13.720 --> 48:14.560
Just a single thread.

48:14.560 --> 48:25.000
And what this incredible paper by Flyxion reveals is that all three of these massive historical phases are fundamentally about a single geometric reality,

48:25.540 --> 48:28.340
how we manage the space of available futures.

48:28.640 --> 48:33.360
The central positive contribution of this paper isn't just an academic warning.

48:33.360 --> 48:39.340
It provides a single, unified diagnostic question that applies at any scale of reality.

48:39.480 --> 48:40.360
And you can apply it anywhere.

48:40.580 --> 48:44.800
You can apply it to a global empire, a corporate supply chain, or a single individual's life.

48:44.920 --> 48:45.660
What is the question?

48:46.060 --> 48:50.520
Does the system increase the density of reachable futures while actively maintaining their diversity?

48:51.420 --> 48:54.580
Does it preserve the repair corridors that make navigation possible?

48:54.880 --> 48:58.900
And does it keep the sensitivity to unexpected shocks within recoverable bounds?

48:59.100 --> 49:02.160
And I want to bring that directly back to you, the listener.

49:02.160 --> 49:04.400
Think about your own life right now.

49:04.800 --> 49:07.960
Your career, your finances, your relationships.

49:08.520 --> 49:09.280
Good diagnostic.

49:09.620 --> 49:11.280
Are you living in the fragility regime?

49:11.560 --> 49:13.300
Are you just maximizing volume?

49:13.740 --> 49:20.380
Are you just chasing the highest possible salary, the biggest network, the fastest growth, the most efficient daily routine?

49:20.440 --> 49:21.280
Which all feels good.

49:21.340 --> 49:21.980
It feels great.

49:21.980 --> 49:25.860
But are you actively, deliberately maintaining your entropy?

49:26.500 --> 49:29.580
Are you preserving independent repair corridors?

49:30.220 --> 49:38.580
If your primary pathway, your main source of income, or your core skill set fails tomorrow, do you have a structurally distinct fallback?

49:38.720 --> 49:39.680
That's the real test.

49:39.680 --> 49:45.960
Or has your life become so hyper-optimized and homogenized that a single shock will send you off the cliff?

49:46.320 --> 49:47.960
It's a profound personal diagnostic.

49:48.620 --> 49:53.200
As the paper implies, the silent killer of success isn't always an obvious dramatic failure.

49:54.000 --> 49:59.720
Most often, the silent killer is the quiet, highly efficient loss of distinct futures.

49:59.720 --> 50:03.500
And that leads me to a final provocative thought for you to mull over.

50:03.640 --> 50:04.040
Let's hear it.

50:04.180 --> 50:08.920
We spent a lot of time today talking about bottlenecks, collapse, and fragility.

50:09.120 --> 50:10.340
It can feel a bit bleak.

50:10.580 --> 50:11.060
It can.

50:11.360 --> 50:15.520
But there is a powerful thread of hope embedded deep in the math of this paper.

50:15.780 --> 50:19.720
The author briefly mentions theorem for repair generation.

50:19.920 --> 50:20.180
Right.

50:20.320 --> 50:26.060
And they note that the theory of recovery is the theory of what restores repair generation after collapse.

50:26.060 --> 50:34.020
The paper cites things like completely novel scientific discovery, radical institutional innovation, and ontology revision.

50:34.180 --> 50:37.940
Ontology revision meaning completely changing how we view reality itself.

50:38.360 --> 50:43.220
Deliberately opening up new, previously unimaginable pathways to positive states.

